9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 433, L.D. 665, “An Act Regarding the
10 Use of Military Protective Orders in Protection from Abuse and Protection from
11 Harassment Proceedings”
12 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 2 and inserting the following:
13 'Sec. 2. 5 MRSA §4654, sub-§2, as amended by PL 2011, c. 559, Pt. C, §§4 and 5,
14 is further amended by enacting at the end a new first blocked paragraph to read:
15 In making the determination required under paragraph A, the court may consider the
16 existence of an active military protective order.'
17 Amend the bill by striking out all of section 7.
18 Amend the bill in section 8 in subsection 1 in the 5th and 6th lines (page 2, lines 12
19 and 13 in L.D.) by striking out the following: "or the existence of an active military
20 protective order on behalf of the plaintiff against the defendant"
21 Amend the bill in section 8 in subsection 1 in the 6th line (page 2, line 13 in L.D.) by
22 inserting after the following: "cause." the following: 'In determining whether good cause
23 exists, the court may consider the existence of an active military protective order.'
24 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
25 number to read consecutively.
26 SUMMARY
2277 This amendment provides that the court may consider the existence of a military
2288 protective order when determining whether to grant a request for a temporary protection
2299 order in protection from abuse and protection from harassment hearings, rather than relying
3300 on a military protective order as the sole basis for a temporary protection order under the
3311 protection from abuse and protection from harassment statutes, as proposed in the bill.
